ea, Michael (2015). [http://www.mitpressjournals.org/doi/abs/10.1162/LEON_a_00936#.VZ0zyabfjsY \"Karakuri: Subtle Trickery in Device Art and Robotics Demonstrations at Miraikan\"] ''Leonardo'' 48(1): 40-47.</ref>\n\n''Karakuri'' is alternatively written in Japanese [[kanji]] as {{nihongo2|\u7d61\u7e70\u308a}}, {{nihongo2|\u7d61\u7e70}}, {{nihongo2|\u6a5f\u5de7}}, {{nihongo2|\u6a5f\u95a2}}, and archaically as {{nihongo2|\u5510\u7e70}}.\n\n== History ==\nKarakuri emerged in Japan during the introduction of the European clock making technology sometime in the early 17th century.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Robots that Talk and Listen: Technology and Social Impact|last=Markowitz|first=Judith|date=2014|publisher=Walter de Gruyter GmbH & Co KG|year=|isbn=9781614516033|location=Berlin|pages=33}}</ref> The country embraced the mechanized puppet performance as a form of entertainment since, becoming popular during the Edo period, which was considered the golden age of karakuri construction and use.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nIn 1662, Takeda Omi completed the first ''butai karakuri''.<ref name=\":0\" /> He then built several of these large puppets for theatrical exhibitions.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nAccording to Kirsty Boyle, a student of one of the last karakuri puppet master in Japan, the karakuri tradition focuses on the art of concealing technology with the belief that it would evoke feelings and emotions more effectively.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cheok|first=Adrian David|url=https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=-MOHDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA2&dq=karakuri+puppet&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiuiNT6kdvnAhWRF6YKHeLrBCoQ6AEIMzAB#v=onepage&q=karakuri%20puppet&f=false|title=Human\u2013Robot Intimate Relationships|last2=Zhang|first2=Emma Yann|date=2019|publisher=Springer|year=|isbn=978-3-319-94729-7|location=Cham|pages=2}}</ref> It is also noted that, although the karakuri puppet resembles the human figure, it has a form of decisive movement that feature rapid shifts that cannot be captured by the naked eye.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hendry|first=Joy|title=Japan at Play|last2=Raveri|first2=Massimo|date=2005|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=0203996569|location=London|pages=74}}</ref> \n\n== Types ==\nThree main types of karakuri exist.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Mechademia 3: Limits of the Human|last=Lunning|first=Frenchy|date=2008|publisher=University of Minnesota Press|year=|isbn=9780816654826|location=Minneapolis, MN|pages=231}}</ref> {{nihongo3|stage karakuri|\u821e\u53f0\u304b\u3089\u304f\u308a|Butai karakuri}} were life-sized dolls designed for public performances such as [[theatre|theatres]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Tokyo Cyberpunk: Posthumanism in Japanese Visual Culture|last=Brown|first=Steven T.|date=2010|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|year=|isbn=9780230103597|location=New York|pages=32}}</ref> {{nihongo3|tatami room karakuri|\u5ea7\u6577\u304b\u3089\u304f\u308a|Zashiki karakuri}} were small and used in homes. {{nihongo3|festival car karakuri|\u5c71\u8eca\u304b\u3089\u304f\u308a|Dashi karakuri}} were large mechanical dolls used in religious festivals<ref name=\":1\" />, where the puppets were used to perform reenactments of traditional [[mythology|myth]]s and [[legend]]s. \n\nSome scholars note that the gestures and movements of the karakuri have influenced the [[Noh]], [[Kabuki]]<ref name=\":0\" /> and [[Bunraku]] theatre.\n\n===Zashiki karakuri===\nThe most common example today of a zashiki karakuri mechanism is a tea-serving robot, which starts moving forward when a cup of tea is placed on the plate in its hands. This karakuri, which is also known as ''chahakobi''.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Bock|first=Thomas|title=Robotic Industrialization|last2=Linner|first2=Thomas|date=2015|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=|isbn=978-1-107-07639-6|location=New York|pages=98}}</ref> was used in a situation when a host wanted to treat a guest in a recreational way. It moves in a straight line for a set distance, moving its feet as if walking, and then bows its head. This signals that the tea is for drinking, and the doll stops when the cup is removed. When it is replaced, the robot raises its head, turns around and returns to where it came from. It is typically powered by a wound spring made of whalebone, and the actions are controlled by a set of cams and levers.\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Tokugawaendashizoroe5.JPG|Dashi karakuri of the ''Tsutsui-ch\u014d/Dekimachi tenn\u014dsai'' in [[Nagoya]].\nFile:Tokugawaendashizoroe6.JPG|\nFile:Tokugawaendashizoroe8.JPG|\nFile:Shimohanda festival1.jpg|''Shimohanda Festival'' in [[Handa, Aichi|Handa]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[Animatronic]]\n*[[Gakutensoku]]\n*[[Japanese robotics]]\n*[[Tanaka Hisashige]]\n*[[Automaton]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Karakuri}}\n*[http://www.karakuri.info/ Karakuri.info] English information site\n* [http://cgi2.nhk.or.jp/michi/cgi/detail.cgi?dasID=D0004200010_00000 Karakuri puppets in Takayama Matsuri Festival][[NHK]](video)\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Karakuri ningyo}}\n[[Category:Puppets]]\n[[Category:Karakuri| ]]\n[[Category:Science and technology during the Edo period]]\n[[Category:Performing arts in Japan]]\n[[Category:Japanese dolls]]\n[[Category:Japanese inventions]]\n[[Category:Historical robots]]\n[[Category:Robots of Japan]]\n[[Category:17th-century robots]]\n[[Category:Entertainment robots]]\n\n{{Puppet-stub}}\n[[Category:Culture articles needing translation from Japanese Wikipedia]]\n", "name_user": "Zentropa", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karakuri_puppet"}
